<paragraph blockId="2.[136,1452,236,677]" box="[189,790,340,365]" pageId="2" pageNumber="142">
Host Plant. 
<taxonomicName authority="(Trin.) Bor" authorityName="Bor" baseAuthorityName="Trin." box="[315,666,340,364]" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Psammochloa" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="2" pageNumber="142" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="villosa">
<emphasis box="[315,544,340,364]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="142">Psammochloa villosa</emphasis>
(Trin.) Bor
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[681,778,340,365]" captionStart="Figures 7–10" captionStartId="3.[155,227,1557,1579]" captionTargetBox="[189,1399,250,1512]" captionTargetId="figure-220@3.[189,1399,250,1512]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figures 7–10. Biological pictures of Eodorcadion (Ornatodorcadion) zhaoi sp. nov. 7. Male on the food plant. 8. Female before oviposition. 9–10. Landscape of the localities." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5360850" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5360850/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="142">Figs 7–8</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[136,1452,236,677]" pageId="2" pageNumber="142">
Biology. Adults are active in the daytime in the sandy deserts (
<figureCitation box="[861,970,375,399]" captionStart="Figures 7–10" captionStartId="3.[155,227,1557,1579]" captionTargetBox="[189,1399,250,1512]" captionTargetId="figure-220@3.[189,1399,250,1512]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figures 7–10. Biological pictures of Eodorcadion (Ornatodorcadion) zhaoi sp. nov. 7. Male on the food plant. 8. Female before oviposition. 9–10. Landscape of the localities." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5360850" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5360850/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="142">Figs 9–10</figureCitation>
) from the middle of August to the beginning of October; the first specimen collected on 
<date box="[593,694,410,434]" pageId="2" pageNumber="142" value="2017-10-01">1.X.2017</date>
, was found at 10: 00 am, while those collected on 
<date box="[1226,1325,410,434]" pageId="2" pageNumber="142" value="2018-10-03">3.X.2018</date>
were found during 9:30–15:00 eating leaves and stems of 
<taxonomicName authority="(Trin.) Bor. Oviposition" authorityName="Bor. Oviposition" baseAuthorityName="Trin." box="[618,1103,444,468]" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Psammochloa" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="2" pageNumber="142" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="villosa">
<emphasis box="[618,846,444,468]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="142">Psammochloa villosa</emphasis>
(Trin.) Bor. Oviposition
</taxonomicName>
takes place on bases of the stems of host plants. Beetles try to escape by quick crawling (cannot fly for hind wings reduced). One individual was videoed on 
<date box="[136,277,514,538]" pageId="2" pageNumber="142" value="2018-08-19">19.VIII.2018</date>
, at the locality which is beside the Tian’ehu (Swan lake) of Alxa Left Banner, Tengger Desert (personal communication with Li Ren and Bao Li, video taken by Jun Du), showing that it can crawl quite fast on the sand.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[136,1452,236,677]" box="[189,594,583,607]" pageId="2" pageNumber="142">
